{"title_page": "Mikayil Yusifov", "text_new": "{{short description|Azerbaijani footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Mikayil Yusifov\n| image       =\n| fullname    =\n| height      = {{height|m=1.85|precision=0}}\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1982|04|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic|Azerbaijani SSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber  =\n| position    = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 = [[Shafa Baku FK|Shafa Baku]]\n| years1 = 1998\u20132004   | clubs1 = [[Shafa Baku FK|Shafa Baku]]           | caps1 = 35 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2004\u20132005   | clubs2 = [[MOIK Baku]]                          | caps2 = 28 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2005\u20132007   | clubs3 = [[Khazar Lankaran FK|Khazar Lankaran]] | caps3 = 17 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2007\u20132008   | clubs4 = [[Kartal S.K.|Kartalspor]]             | caps4 = 3  | goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2008        | clubs5 = [[FK Standard Sumgayit|Standard Baku]] | caps5 = 0  | goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2009\u20132012   | clubs6 = [[FK Mughan|Mughan]]                   | caps6 =    | goals6 =  \n| years7 = 2012\u20132013   | clubs7 = [[Turan-Tovuz IK|Turan-Tovuz]]         | caps7 = 2  | goals7 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2005\n| nationalteam1  = [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| pcupdate = 20 March 2020\n| ntupdate = 20 March 2020\n}}\n''' Mikayil Yusifov ''' (born 24 April 1982 in [[Baku]]) is a retired [[Azerbaijani people|Azerbaijani]] professional [[association football|football]] [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]].\n\n==Career==\nYusifov joined [[FK Khazar Lenkoran]] from [[MOIK Baku]] before the 2005\u201306 season.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/footballeurope/news/kind=2/newsid=319049.html Coaches culled in Azerbaijan]</ref> He later transferred to [[Kartalspor]] in Turkey before the 2007\u201308 season.<ref>[http://news.trendaz.com/?show=news&newsid=1192928&lang=EN Turkish Club Which Mikhail Yusifov Plays for Indebted to Fans: Club\u2019s President]</ref>  His contract with [[Kartalspor]] was cancelled by mutual agreement on 15 August 2008. Shortly after he was presented as the new goalkeeper for [[Standard Baku]].\n\nYusifov made his debut with the [[Azerbaijan national football team]] as a second-half substitute in a friendly against [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|T&T]] on 23 February 2005.<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesf/friend-intres2005.html International Friendly Matches 2005]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{NFT player|pid=24851}}\n* [http://www.tff.org/Default.aspx?pageId=526&kisiId=1064356 Profile at TFF.org]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yusifov, Mikayil}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijani footballers]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijan international footballers]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijani expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijani expatriate sportspeople in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Kartalspor footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Baku]]\n[[Category:FK Standard Sumgayit players]]\n[[Category:MOIK Baku players]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijan Premier League players]]\n[[Category:TFF First League players]]\n\n\n{{Azerbaijan-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Mikayil Yusifov\n| image       =\n| fullname    =\n| height      = {{height|m=1.85|precision=0}}\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1982|04|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic|Azerbaijani SSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber  =\n| position    = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 = [[Shafa Baku FK|Shafa Baku]]\n| years1 = 1998\u20132004   | clubs1 = [[Shafa Baku FK|Shafa Baku]]           | caps1 = 35 | goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2004\u20132005   | clubs2 = [[MOIK Baku]]                          | caps2 = 28 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2005\u20132007   | clubs3 = [[Khazar Lankaran FK|Khazar Lankaran]] | caps3 = 17 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2007\u20132008   | clubs4 = [[Kartal S.K.|Kartalspor]]             | caps4 = 3  | goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2008        | clubs5 = [[FK Standard Sumgayit|Standard Baku]] | caps5 = 0  | goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2009\u20132012   | clubs6 = [[FK Mughan|Mughan]]                   | caps6 =    | goals6 =  \n| years7 = 2012\u20132013   | clubs7 = [[Turan-Tovuz IK|Turan-Tovuz]]         | caps7 = 2  | goals7 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2005\n| nationalteam1  = [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| pcupdate = 20 March 2020\n| ntupdate = 20 March 2020\n}}\n''' Mikayil Yusifov ''' (born 24 April 1982 in [[Baku]]) is a retired [[Azerbaijani people|Azerbaijani]] professional [[association football|football]] [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]].\n\n==Career==\nYusifov joined [[FK Khazar Lenkoran]] from [[MOIK Baku]] before the 2005\u201306 season.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/footballeurope/news/kind=2/newsid=319049.html Coaches culled in Azerbaijan]</ref> He later transferred to [[Kartalspor]] in Turkey before the 2007\u201308 season.<ref>[http://news.trendaz.com/?show=news&newsid=1192928&lang=EN Turkish Club Which Mikhail Yusifov Plays for Indebted to Fans: Club\u2019s President]</ref>  His contract with [[Kartalspor]] was cancelled by mutual agreement on 15 August 2008. Shortly after he was presented as the new goalkeeper for [[Standard Baku]].\n\nYusifov made his debut with the [[Azerbaijan national football team]] as a second-half substitute in a friendly against [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|T&T]] on 23 February 2005.<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesf/friend-intres2005.html International Friendly Matches 2005]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{NFT player|pid=24851}}\n* [http://www.tff.org/Default.aspx?pageId=526&kisiId=1064356 Profile at TFF.org]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yusifov, Mikayil}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijani footballers]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijan international footballers]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijani expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijani expatriate sportspeople in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Kartalspor footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Baku]]\n[[Category:FK Standard Sumgayit players]]\n[[Category:MOIK Baku players]]\n[[Category:Azerbaijan Premier League players]]\n[[Category:TFF First League players]]\n\n\n{{Azerbaijan-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Azerbaijani footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Azerbaijani footballer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mikayil_Yusifov"}
{"title_page": "Trichonephila edulis", "text_new": "{{italictitle}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Female Nephila Edulis SeanMcClean 2007.jpg\n| image_caption = Female ''Nephila edulis'', [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]], [[Western Australia]].<ref>[http://www.xs4all.nl/~ednieuw/australian/nephila/Nephila.html Golden orb weavers] Ed Nieuwenhuys, Ronald Loggen 1997, 2002, Jurgen Otto 2005. Retrieved 2007-04-07.</ref>\n| taxon = Trichonephila edulis\n| authority = ([[Jacques Labillardi\u00e8re|Labillardi\u00e8re]], 1799)<ref name=WSC_s22442/>\n| range_map = Distribution.nephila.edulis.1.png\n|| synonyms =\n<small>\n''Aranea edulis''<br />\n''Epeira edulis''<br />\n''Nephila edulis''<br />\n''Nephila imperatrix''<br />\n''Nephila eremiana''<br />\n</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Trichonephila edulis''''' is a species of large spider of the family [[Araneidae]], formerly placed in the genus ''[[Nephila]]''. It is referred to the common name Australian golden orb weaver.<ref>arachne.org.au http://www.arachne.org.au</ref> It is found in [[Australia]], in both tropical and temperate regions, and in parts of [[New Guinea]] and [[New Caledonia]].\n\nIt has a large body size variability, females can reach a body length of up to 40 millimetres, males about 7&nbsp;mm. The [[cephalothorax]] is black with a white pattern on the back, and a yellow underside; the [[abdomen]] is grey to brown.\n\nThe web is about 1 metre in diameter and protected on one or both sides by a strong \"barrier\" web. ''T. edulis'' breeds from February to May, and produces an average of 380 eggs.\n\n==Name==\nThe species was first collected and named by [[Jacques Labillardiere]], in [[Relation du Voyage \u00e0 la Recherche de la P\u00e9rouse]] (1799),<ref>Labillardi\u00e8re, J. 1799. Relation du voyage \u00e0 la recherche de La P\u00e9rouse, fait par ordre de l'Assembl\u00e9e constituante. Paris Vol. 2 pp. 240-241</ref> becoming the second Australian spider to be described by a European naturalist.<ref name=\"AFDb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.environment.gov.au/biodiversity/abrs/online-resources/fauna/afd/taxa/Araneae|title=Order Araneae: Spiders|last=Davies|first=Valerie Todd |date=30 Mar 2006|work=Australian Faunal Directory|publisher=Government of Australia|accessdate=2009-03-06|display-authors=etal}}</ref> The first was ''[[Gasteracantha fornicata]]''.\n\nThe species name ''edulis'' means \"edible\" in Latin. [[Jacques Labillardiere|Labillardiere]] wrote: \"Les habitans de la Nouvelle-Cal\u00e9donie appellent '''''nougui''''' cette esp\u00e8ce d'araign\u00e9e, que je d\u00e9signe sous le nom d' aranea edulis (araign\u00e9e que les Cal\u00e9doniens mangent).\" (The inhabitants of New Caledonia call this spider \"nougui\". I have described it under the name Aranea edulis, meaning spiders that the New Caledonians eat.)\n\nSeveral related spiders are considered a [[delicacy]] in [[New Guinea]], \"plucked by the legs from their webs and lightly roasted over an open fire\".<ref>Meyer Rochow, V.B. (1973). Edible insects in three different ethnic groups of Papua and New Guinea. ''Am J. Clin. Nutr.'' 26:673-677.</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Uhl, G. & Vollrath, F (2000). Extreme body size variability in the golden silk spider (''Nephila edulis'') does not extend to genitalia. ''J. Zool. Lond.'' 251:7-14 [https://web.archive.org/web/20070610153023/http://www.zoologie.uni-bonn.de/NeuroEthologie/Deutsch/Mitarbeiter/GUhl/pdfs/00uv01.pdf PDF]\n*Vollrath, F., Madsen, B. & Shao, Z. (2001). The effect of spinning conditions on the mechanics of a spider's dragline silk. ''Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences'' 268:2339-2346 [http://www.journals.royalsoc.ac.uk/(q5jjhb45xankycfrwatybrnk)/app/home/content.asp?referrer=contribution&format=2&page=1&pagecount=8 PDF]{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{DOI|10.1098/rspb.2001.1590}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=WSC_s22442>{{cite web |title=Taxon details ''Trichonephila edulis'' (Labillardiere, 1799) |work=World Spider Catalog |publisher=Natural History Museum Bern |url=http://www.wsc.nmbe.ch/species/22442 |accessdate=2020-04-29 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Gallery==\n{{Gallery | title = Images of ''T. edulis''|align=center\n|File:Nephila_edulis_side.jpg|Side view, Sydney female\n|File:Nephila_edulis_back.jpg|Back view, Sydney female\n|File:Nephila_edulis_front.jpg|Bottom view, Sydney female\n|File:Nephila_edulis_female.JPG|Back view, Western Australia female\n|File:A169, Mary Kathleen, Queensland, Australia, golden orb weaver spider and locust, 2007.JPG|A Queensland female and a locust fight in its web\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Wikispecies-inline}}\n* [http://www.conservationinstitute.org/pcn/invertebrates/golden_orb_web_spiders.htm Pictures and info]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060813190110/http://food-insects.com/Vol6%20no2.htm The Food Insect Newsletter, July 1993]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2338293}}\n\n[[Category:Araneidae]]\n[[Category:Spiders of Australia]]\n[[Category:Spiders described in 1799]]\n", "text_old": "{{italictitle}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| image = Female Nephila Edulis SeanMcClean 2007.jpg\n| image_caption = Female ''Nephila edulis'', [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]], [[Western Australia]].<ref>[http://www.xs4all.nl/~ednieuw/australian/nephila/Nephila.html Golden orb weavers] Ed Nieuwenhuys, Ronald Loggen 1997, 2002, Jurgen Otto 2005. Retrieved 2007-04-07.</ref>\n| taxon = Trichonephila edulis\n| authority = ([[Jacques Labillardi\u00e8re|Labillardi\u00e8re]], 1799)<ref name=WSC_s22442/>\n| range_map = Distribution.nephila.edulis.1.png\n|| synonyms =\n<small>\n''Aranea edulis''<br />\n''Epeira edulis''<br />\n''Nephila edulis''<br />\n''Nephila imperatrix''<br />\n''Nephila eremiana''<br />\n</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Trichonephila edulis''''' is a species of large spider of the family [[Araneidae]], formerly placed in the genus ''[[Nephila]]''. It is referred to the common name Australian golden orb weaver.<ref>arachne.org.au http://www.arachne.org.au</ref> It is found in [[Australia]], in both tropical and temperate regions, and in parts of [[New Guinea]] and [[New Caledonia]].\n\nIt has a large body size variability, females can reach a body length of up to 40 millimetres, males about 7&nbsp;mm. The [[cephalothorax]] is black with a white pattern on the back, and a yellow underside; the [[abdomen]] is grey to brown.\n\nThe web is about 1 metre in diameter and protected on one or both sides by a strong \"barrier\" web. ''N. edulis'' breeds from February to May, and produces an average of 380 eggs.\n\n==Name==\nThe species was first collected and named by [[Jacques Labillardiere]], in [[Relation du Voyage \u00e0 la Recherche de la P\u00e9rouse]] (1799),<ref>Labillardi\u00e8re, J. 1799. Relation du voyage \u00e0 la recherche de La P\u00e9rouse, fait par ordre de l'Assembl\u00e9e constituante. Paris Vol. 2 pp. 240-241</ref> becoming the second Australian spider to be described by a European naturalist.<ref name=\"AFDb\">{{cite web|url=http://www.environment.gov.au/biodiversity/abrs/online-resources/fauna/afd/taxa/Araneae|title=Order Araneae: Spiders|last=Davies|first=Valerie Todd |date=30 Mar 2006|work=Australian Faunal Directory|publisher=Government of Australia|accessdate=2009-03-06|display-authors=etal}}</ref> The first was ''[[Gasteracantha fornicata]]''.\n\nThe species name ''edulis'' means \"edible\" in Latin. [[Jacques Labillardiere|Labillardiere]] wrote: \"Les habitans de la Nouvelle-Cal\u00e9donie appellent '''''nougui''''' cette esp\u00e8ce d'araign\u00e9e, que je d\u00e9signe sous le nom d' aranea edulis (araign\u00e9e que les Cal\u00e9doniens mangent).\" (The inhabitants of New Caledonia call this spider \"nougui\". I have described it under the name Aranea edulis, meaning spiders that the New Caledonians eat.)\n\nSeveral related spiders are considered a [[delicacy]] in [[New Guinea]], \"plucked by the legs from their webs and lightly roasted over an open fire\".<ref>Meyer Rochow, V.B. (1973). Edible insects in three different ethnic groups of Papua and New Guinea. ''Am J. Clin. Nutr.'' 26:673-677.</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Uhl, G. & Vollrath, F (2000). Extreme body size variability in the golden silk spider (''Nephila edulis'') does not extend to genitalia. ''J. Zool. Lond.'' 251:7-14 [https://web.archive.org/web/20070610153023/http://www.zoologie.uni-bonn.de/NeuroEthologie/Deutsch/Mitarbeiter/GUhl/pdfs/00uv01.pdf PDF]\n*Vollrath, F., Madsen, B. & Shao, Z. (2001). The effect of spinning conditions on the mechanics of a spider's dragline silk. ''Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences'' 268:2339-2346 [http://www.journals.royalsoc.ac.uk/(q5jjhb45xankycfrwatybrnk)/app/home/content.asp?referrer=contribution&format=2&page=1&pagecount=8 PDF]{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{DOI|10.1098/rspb.2001.1590}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=WSC_s22442>{{cite web |title=Taxon details ''Trichonephila edulis'' (Labillardiere, 1799) |work=World Spider Catalog |publisher=Natural History Museum Bern |url=http://www.wsc.nmbe.ch/species/22442 |accessdate=2020-04-29 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Gallery==\n{{Gallery | title = Images of ''T. edulis''|align=center\n|File:Nephila_edulis_side.jpg|Side view, Sydney female\n|File:Nephila_edulis_back.jpg|Back view, Sydney female\n|File:Nephila_edulis_front.jpg|Bottom view, Sydney female\n|File:Nephila_edulis_female.JPG|Back view, Western Australia female\n|File:A169, Mary Kathleen, Queensland, Australia, golden orb weaver spider and locust, 2007.JPG|A Queensland female and a locust fight in its web\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Wikispecies-inline}}\n* [http://www.conservationinstitute.org/pcn/invertebrates/golden_orb_web_spiders.htm Pictures and info]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060813190110/http://food-insects.com/Vol6%20no2.htm The Food Insect Newsletter, July 1993]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2338293}}\n\n[[Category:Araneidae]]\n[[Category:Spiders of Aus